definition.value: A disaccharide derivative consisting of a alpha-D-mannosyl residue glycosidically linked to a 5-aminopentyl group and which carries at O-2 a beta-D-mannosyl residue.
ROS Inhibitors
A member of the class of aminoquinolines that is quinoline substituted by methyl and 2-(4-phenylcyclohexylidene)hydrazinyl groups at positions 2 and 4, respectively. It inhibits ROS production.

A pyrrolopyrimidine that is 3,5-dihydro-4H-pyrrolo[3,2-d]pyrimidin-4-one substituted by [2-(2,5-difluoroanilino)-2-hydroxyethyl]sulfanediyl, ethyl, and phenyl groups at positions 2, 3, and 7, respectively. It inhibits androgen-induced ROS production.
Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A primary alpha-hydroxy ketone that is 3-methylbutane-1,2-diol in which the hydroxy group at position 2 has been formally oxidised to give the corresponding ketone.
A member of the class of cyclohexanones that is cyclohexanone substituted by methyl groups at positions 3 and 5.
A methyl ketone that is cyclohexane substituted by an acetyl group at position 1.
An alkylaminium that is the conjugate acid of pentan-1-amine resulting from the protonation of the primary amino group; Major species at pH 7.3.
Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
Major microspecies at pH 7.3.

A member of the class of benzodioxoles that is 1,3-benzodioxole substituted by a (2-anilino-5-oxo-1,5-dihydro-4H-imidazol-4-ylidene)methyl group at position 5. It is an inhibitor of DYRK1A, DYRK2, CLK1, and CLK3 (IC50s = 0.04, 0.035, 0.015, and 4.5 muM, respectively).
An indoloquinoline that is 11H-indolo[3,2-c]quinoline substituted by carboxy and iodo groups at positions 6 and 10, respectively. It is a potent inhibitor of DYRK1A (IC50 = 6 nM).
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion corresponding to the conjugate base of (R)-mevaldic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic heterotetracyclic compound that is any indole fused to a quinoline ring.
An EC 2.7.12.* [dual-specificity kinases (those acting on Ser/Thr and Tyr residues)] inhibitor that inhibits the action of dual-specificity kinase (EC 2.7.12.1).
An alpha-amino-acid cation obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group and protonation of the amino and guanidino groups of (4S)-4-hydroxy-L-arginine; major microspecies at pH 7.3.
An organic cation obtained by abstraction of a hydride from position 7 of 2,6,9-trimethyl-13-oxatetracyclo[6.3.1.1(6,9).0(1,5)]tridecane.

An indolyl carboxylate ester that is 1H-indole substituted by methoxycarbonyl and (E)-(8-oxo-1,5,6,8-tetrahydro-2H-1,5-methanopyrido[1,2-a][1,5]diazocin-3(4H)-yl)diazenyl groups at positions 2 and 3, respectively. It targets the enoyl reductase domain of fungal fatty acid synthase, exhibits broad-spectrum antifungal activity, is bioactive against the filamentous mold, Aspergillus fumigatus and has minimal mammalian cytotoxicity.

A secondary carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of N-(naphthalen-1-ylcarbonyl)glycine with the amino group of 2-(3-methoxyphenoxy)aniline. It is a first-in-class small molecule inhibitor of PCNA, a protein essential for DNA replication and repair within tumours.
An inhibitor that interferes with the action of PCNA.

A C-nitro compound that is benzene substituted by [4-(methylamino)benzoyl]oxy, nitro, nitro, and (3,3-dimethyl-2-oxido-2lambda(5)-triaz-1-en-1-yl)oxy groups at positions 1, 2, 4, and 5, respectively. It is an anti-cancer compound that is designed to release NO upon activation by glutathione.
Octaanion of 1D-myo-inositol 1,2,3,6-tetrakisphosphate arising from global deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups. Major species at pH 7.3.
